    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-06-01T00:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-06-01T00:30:00-05:00" n="928"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d928">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">746E.00/6–152: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Ceylon</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GBA1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gufler</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential<lb/>priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Colombo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-06-01T11:00:00+05:30"
                            >June 1, 1952—11 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>650. With results all 95 districts announced, following is parties standing in
                    order gains, losses, total: <gloss target="#t_UNP1">UNP</gloss> 23, 12, 54;
                    Freedom Party 6, 6, 9; LSSP 1, 6, 9; Front 0, 2, 4; Tamil <gloss
                        target="#t_Cong1">Cong</gloss> 0, 1, 4; Federalist 1, 1, 2; Moors 2, 0, 2;
                    Labor 1, 1, 1; Peoples Republican 0, 1, 1; Independents including speaker 5, 2,
                    9. Of 7 former Indian <gloss target="#t_Cong1">Cong</gloss> seats, <gloss
                        target="#t_UNP1">UNP</gloss> won 6, Labor 1.</p>
                <p>Among last day victors were <gloss target="#t_MinFin1">MinFin</gloss>
                    Jayewardene, Freedom Party leader <persName corresp="#p_BSWRD1"
                        >Bandaranaike</persName>, LSSP leader Perera, English wife of <gloss
                        target="#t_CP1">CP</gloss> leader Wickermasinghe. Losers include
                    Wickermasinghe, Federalist President Chelvanayakam, Parl Sec Home Min
                    Kanagaratnam, Freedom Party Sri Nissanka.</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_UNP1">UNP</gloss> having clear majority <persName
                        corresp="#p_SDS2">Senanayake</persName> remains <gloss target="#t_PriMin1"
                        >PriMin</gloss> and expected choose new Cabinet within few days.</p>
                <p>Among factors that contributed to <gloss target="#t_UNP1">UNP</gloss> victory are
                    following: (1) sentimental reaction to death former <gloss target="#t_PriMin1"
                        >PriMin</gloss> and energetic personal campaign by <gloss
                        target="#t_PriMin1">PriMin</gloss> who promised carry out father’s policies
                    (this was principal factor mentioned by <gloss target="#t_PriMin1"
                        >PriMin</gloss> in interview with <gloss target="#t_AP1">AP</gloss>
                    representatives); (2) support principal Buddhist and Christian religious
                    leaders; (3) effective use Indian citizenship and immigration question by
                    presentation <gloss target="#t_UNP1">UNP</gloss> as only reliable defense
                    against Indian “imperialism” opposition mishandled this issue and continued see
                    greatest foreign threat in Anglo-American “imperialism”; (4) appeal to
                    traditionalist conservatism villagers through anti-Marxist campaign labeling
                    opposition as enemies religion and agents Soviet imperialism; (5) bad strategy
                    opposition parties which made outward motions toward cooperation but actually
                    fought each other. Apparent alliance, however, enabled <gloss target="#t_UNP1"
                        >UNP</gloss> include Freedom Party in anti-Marxist attacks; <pb facs="0471"
                        n="1521" xml:id="pg_1521"/> (6) superior <gloss target="#t_UNP1">UNP</gloss>
                    organization, large campaign fund, and support entire English and Sinhalese
                    daily press; (7) order of polling with <gloss target="#t_UNP1">UNP</gloss> held
                    constituencies placed first.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GBA1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gufler</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
